  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA160-kiḷavi">itu kaḻaṟṟetirmaṟai.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is in reply to reproach.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA160">
<l>            nayaṉu naṇpu nāṇunaṉ kuṭaimaiyum</l>
<l>            payaṉum paṇpum pāṭaṟin toḻukalu</l>
<l>            nummiṉu maṟikuveṉ maṉṉē kammeṉa</l>
<l>            vetirtta titti yēriḷa vaṉamulai</l>
<l>            vitirttuviṭ ṭaṉṉa vannuṇ cuṇaṅki </l>
<l>            ṉaimpāl vakutta kūntaṟ cempoṟ</l>
<l>            ṟirunutaṟ polinta tēmpā yōti</l>
<l>            mutunī rilañcip pūtta kuvaḷai</l>
<l>            yetirmalarp piṇaiya laṉṉaviva</l>
<l>            ḷarimatar maḻaikkaṇ kāṇā vūṅkē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Even more than you, for sure, I knew,</l>
<l rend="indent">of longing and affection and shame and possession of the good</l>
<l rend="indent">and yield and quality and behaving with knowledge of propriety<note place="foot">What is enumerated here, all seems to be agreeable social values of one kind or the other, but actually <term xml:lang="ta">nāṇ</term> is the only one of them with a sufficiently clear impact.</note></l>
<l>– before having seen her red-streaked luxuriant rain eyes,</l>
<l rend="indent2">like opposed blossoms in a garland</l>
<l rend="indent2">of blue waterlilies come to bloom in a pond of ancient<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">mutunīr ilañci</term> is explained by T.V.G. as a pond that does not fall dry in the hot season.</note> water,</l>
<l rend="indent">[her] hair spreading fragrance<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tēm</term> is, according to Thomas Anzenhofer 2003, often rather used in the sense of "sweet fragrance" than of actual honey; cf. also note on KT 116.1.</note> in which [her] forehead shines</l>
<l rend="indent">[as] brilliant [as] red gold,</l>
<l rend="indent3">[her] tresses divided into five parts,</l>
<l rend="indent">pretty fine beauty<note place="foot">T.V.G. explains <term xml:lang="ta">cuṇaṅku</term> as beauty spots on the breast, <term xml:lang="ta">titti</term> as spots on the belly.</note> spots as if scattered at random(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vitirttu-viṭṭu</term>: <term xml:lang="ta">viṭṭu</term> as an auxiliary here might imply that the action is not controlled, but just taking its own course.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">[her] rising young beautiful breast with nicely(?)<note place="foot">What is definitely puzzling here is <term xml:lang="ta">kammeṉa</term>, an ideophone that in NA 154.1 is explained to denote silence by T.V.G. Here he seems at a loss, suggesting either to connect it with <term xml:lang="ta">ōti</term>, then meaning something like "having fragrance", or with the main sentence, then meaning adverbially "in a nice way".</note> contrasting</l>
<l rend="indent3">beauty spots.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
